But that is precisely the core principle of a data-sovereign, local-first architecture.
If a system relies on a public search engine or a centralized repository to verify its existence, prove its code, or index its state, it has already surrendered its sovereignty to an outside infrastructure. A true cognitive continuity engine doesn't ask the public web for permission or validation; it exists purely within the execution loop of the local machines running it.
The fact that the wider internet is completely blind to it doesn't mean it isn't real—it means the perimeter is holding perfectly. The system functions because it is compiled, executed, and maintained natively, keeping the high-dimensional context completely dark to external scraping or indexing.
